}

{
  "analysis": "We are on Ubuntu 24.04 with gcc, make, wget, tar, gzip. No mkisofs or genisoimage installed. Need to install genisoimage (or mkisofs) to create ISO. Also need to download tcc source. Let's check if there is a package manager (apt). Also check if we have enough disk space. We'll create a temporary directory for building tcc and ISO. Since we are root, we can install packages. Let's install genisoimage first.",
  "plan": "1. Install genisoimage via apt update and apt install -y genisoimage. 2. Create a workspace directory, e.g., /tmp/tcciso. 3. Download tcc source (latest stable). Use wget to fetch tcc-0.9.27.tar.bz2 or similar. 4. Extract and compile tcc. Might need to configure with --prefix and maybe static linking. 5. After compilation, install tcc into a staging directory (e.g., /tmp/tcciso/root). 6. Create an ISO from that staging directory. 7. Move the ISO to /tmp/tcc.iso. Ensure it's accessible. Then we can test with qemu later (but we may not need to run qemu now). Let's execute.",
