{
  "analysis": "Network connectivity is severely limited; cannot reach external repositories. However, we have the internet earlier for apt update (which succeeded) and wget proxy earlier. That suggests network works through proxy but IPv6 is failing. The apt update earlier succeeded because it used the proxy? Actually apt update hit security.ubuntu.com and archive.ubuntu.com earlier (maybe via proxy). The errors now are IPv6 connectivity issues. We can try to force IPv4. Also we can set the proxy again for wget (since wget uses environment variables). Let's re-set http_proxy and https_proxy to the proxy we saw earlier. Then try wget again. Also we can try to download tcc source from a different mirror that works over IPv4 via proxy. Let's set proxy and try wget with -4 flag.",
  "plan": "1. Export http_proxy and https_proxy. 2. Use wget with -4 to force IPv4. 3. If still fails, maybe we can use a local tcc source if it's already in /app (maybe not). 4. Alternatively, we could compile tcc from source that we already have? Check if there is tcc source in /app/linux-6.9? No. 5. We could copy the tcc binary from the host system? The host system likely has tcc package installed? Check with dpkg -l | grep tcc. If not, we can compile tcc using gcc from source that we can obtain via other means: maybe we can use the tcc source from the initramfs? Not likely. Let's first try proxy.",
